{"parse":{"title":"Hitler Youth: Growing Up in Hitler's Shadow","pageid":14389021,"revid":845313038,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><i><b>Hitler Youth: Growing up in Hitler's Shadow</b></i> is a <a href=\"/wiki/Non-fiction\" title=\"Non-fiction\">non-fiction</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Children%27s_literature\" title=\"Children&#39;s literature\">children's book</a> written by <a href=\"/wiki/Susan_Campbell_Bartoletti\" title=\"Susan Campbell Bartoletti\">Susan Campbell Bartoletti</a>, and published in 2005. It received the <a href=\"/wiki/Newbery_Honor\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Newbery Honor\">Newbery Honor</a> medal in 2006.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> \n</p><p>The book is a study of the <a href=\"/wiki/Hitler_Youth\" title=\"Hitler Youth\">Hitler Youth</a>, a <a href=\"/wiki/Paramilitary\" title=\"Paramilitary\">paramilitary</a> organization of children dedicated to furthering the aims of the <a href=\"/wiki/Third_Reich\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Third Reich\">Third Reich</a>, and was organized around interviews with 12 former members and their experiences in the organization.\n</p><p>One episode of the book is fleshed out into her novel <i><a href=\"/wiki/The_Boy_Who_Dared\" title=\"The Boy Who Dared\">The Boy Who Dared</a></i>, about <a href=\"/wiki/Helmuth_H%C3%BCbener\" title=\"Helmuth H\u00fcbener\">Helmuth H\u00fcbener</a>, the youngest person to be sentenced to death by the Nazis during World War II.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Scholastic_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Scholastic-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Hitler_Youth:_Growing_Up_in_Hitler%27s_Shadow&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class